segments.text: Let's stop and see and hope that it's working.
The YMCA in those days was a prominent edifice that housed the Casey's Confectionery downstairs.
It had a few rooms which were used for meetings of some sort, which I was never aware of.
Monday and Tuesday and Thursday and Friday nights it was a locale for Yale practice.
Yale practice was mandatory for all students and enforced pretty harshly by the seniors.
The time to be there was about six
and it lasted until about 720 or so.
The band would be up on the upper veranda, I guess you'd call it, and the L-Eaters and the others that were going to speak
performed about midway up on the steps.
The freshmen and the sophomores would be on the walk between the building and the front first curve.
And then the, I beg your pardon, it'd be just the freshmen that were on the first curve.
Sophomores
and juniors were half and half in the street in the sequence.
And then the seniors were behind the the curve on the side toward the Puryear Hall.
One incident that's worth telling there is that the live oak trees on the space between the
street and the furrier dorm were fairly close together and if some unsuspecting soul had the misfortune to leave his car parked where the the out practice was to be held why the one
enough freshmen had arrived.
They literally would pick that car up and put it over between the trees.
And at the time, there were a couple of trees that just fit a car just about snowed.
So when the owner of the car, he had to bring the yell practices over no matter what.
And then whenever he came, he had the devil of a time getting that thing out of there.
Now, yell practices were normally held how often?
Well, during the football season, if it was a way game, then they were Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, Friday.
If it was a home game, the Friday was a midnight yell practice.
And was it held in the stadium, midnight yell practice?
No.
I'll tell you, I kind of have to hedge on that.
I believe we're going.
But that's the only time.
They never got away any other time.
What about Guyon Hall?
What happened at Guyon Hall?
Well, it was a sort of a formal auditorium.
Of course, it wouldn't have very many people.
Dedications or things like that were there, but most of the students didn't, weren't really aware of it, although that was a, it was served as a movie theater.
Did you all have movies there regularly?
For a reason or so, yeah.
And was there chapel services?
May have been, but I don't remember being there.
Can you think of, were there religious activities related to the community that you remember?
Did many students on the weekend go to a worship service anywhere?
Well, various denominations had churches or
I know that there were great football teams at A&M
in your first years tell me about those about football season well of course we arrived there in september of 40 with the team being the national champions from the year before and we we thoroughly
made the most of every opportunity we could to see the team.
Of course, you had a student activity card, which was part of the enrollment process, which paid for all the athletic events, so there was no problem in going.
And of course, there were special sections for
Freshmen knew where they were to be, and the sophomores and juniors knew where they were to be, and seniors were always up around the 50-yard line.
Where?
Were you all on the east side of Kyle Field?
Yes.
And did the Corps... From the 50-yard line north.
Did the Corps march in before the game?
No, the march in was...
I don't know when they began, but it was in much more recent times.
What about halftime?
What did the band do in those days?
Well, the band, of course, was always exemplary.
Was their routine similar to what it is now?
Well, the difference is they would go through a block arrangement and in and out and cross over and so forth, and then they would end up
and spell out the opposing team or school.
They would trail out, and they'd end up spelling out the name of the school.
And then, once that was evident to the crowd, boy, they would evolve in under Texas Aggies and Marshall Field.
So they did Texas Aggies, not a block T. Normally it is.
Spelling out, spelling out the, at least the home, the other schools just spell out their own team.
We always, A&M always spell out the opponent and our Texas Aggies.
And during those years, those pre-war years, particularly your freshman year, were any of the football players on the campus considered more glamorous?
or were the athletes just like everybody else in terms of the way you felt about them?
Well, most of them lived in Dawn 12, at least in 1940, and that way they could kind of be there and have their own meals in Duncan and Storm, but
They were in the Corps.
In my semester, in the fall of 42, Errol Calley, who played Ian.
C-O-W-L-E-Y?
Yeah.
Errol was a great guy, and he lived with us when he was born.
In fact, I think it must have been in the middle of 42 that the school took out the exclusive phone for the athletes.
So Errol came to live with us, and JB Montgomery, he was in G Battery down below us.
All right.
Other groups, other student activity groups that attracted a lot of attention, the band, were there singing cadets then?
Yes, the singing cadets were there, and they performed.
Occasionally, I don't know what kind of schedule it was, but their shark band was there.
Was there a student government?
Oh, yeah.
I'll give you a quick guess on that.
Yeah, there was.
There was two together.
Do you remember any major, before you and your colleagues go away to the war, do you remember any major arguments the students had with the administration?
Any changes y'all were trying to?
The main thing was to save our boys in June of 42.
Okay.
We had gone into the war and Major General George H. Moore was
became a hero at Brigadier was O'Connor.
Describe him.
Tell me about him.
Well, he was a very distinguished looking man.
He had kind of thin hair and little, uh, thinness glasses.
He was, I would say, about six foot one and weighed maybe 200 pounds.
Uh,
But he, in my experience, he'd always been there.
We were diving across Military Walk in Mitchell Hall from Ross Hall, which was Bullard's office.
And we saw him fairly often.
When did he go on active duty?
Well, they called him in sometime in the spring of 42.
Because he was there in the fall of 41, the war started.
He went fairly quickly.
I don't know.
We generally didn't know much about it.
Because he's at Corregidor when it falls, isn't he?
Yes.
All right, let's go to the war now.
When you got to A&M, the war in Europe had already started.
Did you all assume that the United States was going to be in that war?
All of us did.
What did you think...
the impact was going to be on you?
Well, at that point, if you say where it started, well, of course, the... Let me back up to Pearl Harbor.
We all, going into the fall of 41, we all just, it was a...
more or less an unspoken fact that we would all expect to be called in whenever anything started.
Well, in my case, a group officer had gone down to the campus theater on December the 7th and saw the movie and came out of the movie.
And as we did there in front of the campus theater, right here, everyone was abuzz about the strike at Pearl Harbor.
And we were all just shocked, nothing to do with going to our rooms.
So we all went to our rooms and hurled around our rooms with everything.
Some guys had radios if they listened.
Others, since there was only one telephone per unit, there wasn't much way anybody could call.
So we were there.

uh there were lots of fellas and generally there were lots of fellas that were ready to go right then to volunteer we were all there and we were in the middle of a sophomore year and we were all there to see what was going on but the word was sent around that just stay in
place and wait and see what happened.
Well, there were a number of guys that, oh, the other thing was that you had to volunteer to get in the Navy and you had to volunteer to get in the Air Force.
And there were a number of guys that either they had Deer Johnson, their girlfriend, or they were flunking out, or they were just patriots anyway.
They took off the next morning, on Monday morning, to volunteer.
But most of us were disposed to see what we were, see what would develop.
And the word came down there too that we would stay in school.
and inducted all of us into the Enlisted Reserve Corps.
We would be there at the end until fall.
Right, and so in your case that led, that Enlisted Corps was Army?
Yes.
Okay.
Everything in the school was Army.
If you wanted to go to the Air Force, Air Corps at the time, it was Army Air Force, why you had to volunteer.
So you're, correct me if I'm wrong, I get the impression that you're saying the leadership at A&M encouraged y'all to stay in school and wait for advice on what to do later.
That's the military department.
That's right.
And it took three or four days for that to get shaken up.
You take in my case,
I desperately wanted a degree so that if I made it through the war, I'd have a pad to launch me on.
And that's where most of us were.
We started in our class of, we started in our class of, I believe,
By the time we were called in May of 43, it was 650.
How did the routine on the campus change after the war started?
Well the military was a little more rigorous.
They got going with some
exercise drill.
We had calisthenics in the morning every morning.
We had obstacle courses.
We had to run a two mile lap at least once a week.
As far as I'd say the military text, what it took to understand the science, I would be pleased.
because that's more intensive than it had been before.
Right.
Now, I'm assuming that before December 7, you and your classmates thought the probable enemy was in Europe more than you did in the Far East.
Oh, yeah.
See, in fact, when the man was sort of a forgotten entity, he backed up.
The Germans invaded Russia in 39.
And then that all evolved into the Germans then going into Austria and then they went up into Denmark and Norway.
And then in the summer of 40, just as we were finishing our high school,
the Germans swept through the Netherlands and Belgium and France.
Well, it looked like there was just a juggernaut that didn't have any stopping.
And we were all sobered by that.
And there had been some articles in magazines that I'd read about how the Japanese were moving around in the Far East.
Basically, you could say that the American public had really no knowledge at all of the potentia of Japanese.
Everything the American public knew was that it was a Japanese, it was a cheap imitation.
And very quickly, any Japanese military personnel was a helmeted, I mean,
fabric-helmeted person with a ring of fur around his face and buck teeth and black horn-rimmed glasses.
I later went to Japan looking for him after the war was over.
As the war started, what did you and your classmates think was going to be the result of this war?
Who was going to win it?
Well, there was a lot of apprehension.
I don't think we were ever in doubt that we would eventually win it.
But there was a lot of apprehension about the Japanese because no sooner had Pearl Harbor happened than there became reports of some parachute bombs floating in from the Pacific and so forth.
And there was a real apprehension that the Japs hit Pearl Harbor as a wake-up call and they were going to hit the West Coast.
You said that General Moore went to the Pacific.
As you all heard the news about the Philippines and Bataan and Corregidor, describe your thoughts.
Well, it just extended the shock of Pearl Harbor.
Suddenly the Japanese are running all over the place and taking everything.
And there was very little information coming back.
What was your impression of the leadership of the United States at that time?
Did you have confidence in it?
Yeah, we did.
We didn't have any doubt of it.
I think the only examples I know out now that
where there was doubt of the American leadership.
And I think one of them was Admiral Kimmel at Pearl Harbor.
Whether he was or not, I don't know.
I've been to Pearl Harbor, and I've looked over that setup and the whole thing.
I just, I mean, there was an oversight or a goof there that let that happen.
It would have happened anyway, just as bad as it was.
The other was in North Africa where they canned a bunch of generals early on.
December 8th, did you hear the speech that President Roosevelt made?
Did you hear it on the radio?
Yes.
Where were you?
I don't know.
No, but were you in your dorm room?
They didn't call the student body together, did they?
No.
I don't know.
I guess I was in some sort of room.
I was a sixth grader in Fort Smith, Arkansas, and we went to the school library, I remember.
Let's see, before we let you go away to the war, did you have a car in those pre-war years?
No.
Tell me how you got back and forth to Fort Worth normally.
Well, we all hitchhiked.
Describe that routine.
Well, the Aggies in the 30s,
were the only people that wore uniforms.
And the public got accustomed to that.
And the Aggies also, very few of them ever had any transportation.
So it developed that the Aggies had a routine for hitchhiking whereby there was an agreed upon departure point in each town
up and down the main lines of Texas.
And the custom was that the first guy there put his bag down and he hung out his thumb.
And if he didn't get out before the next guy came, the next guy put his behind, and he waited until the first guy was gone, and then he moved up.
And it was designed in such a way that the public could understand that they only had to take as many as they wanted.
And of course there was always an emphasis, it was not in any official thing, but everybody around the campus made a point saying you gotta be curious and you gotta be helpful and everything.
And it was very popular among the public.
Where, near the campus, where was the departure point?
Well, if you were gonna go to, if you were gonna go north, you had to go into Bryan and out to the
whatever that crossroads is, or the navels was.
There was a crossroads with a highway from Highway 6 going north.
Whatever it is.
Caldwell to Madisonville?
Caldwell to Madisonville.
That was a takeoff point there.
And in those days, you could load six guys in a cab to the quarter all the way to Bryan.
All right, what if you were going to Houston?
Well, if you're going to Houston, Highway 6 was complete past the campus.
You went out to what would be empty now.
We call it the East Gate.
And you put your bag down and stand in line.
One of my experiences along that line was that I went out there.
I was exempt.
in my first year.
And I had a way to get out there and get a ride.
And I was telling him, here came a guy in a red pickup truck.
And I hopped in.
I said, where are you going?
I said, Houston.
He said, well, let's go.
Well, that guy took off down the road like I have never been before or since.
I couldn't even guess how fast he was going.
I was hanging on for dear life.
No conversation, just going.
Finally, I said, what you got in this thing?
Is it magic glycerin?
All I could do is keep holding on until he stopped and I could get out.
During those years, about how often did you go home?
Oh,
Maybe once every two months or something like that.
From A&M to Dallas and Fort Worth, there was one fellow in particular, he had a station wagon and he had a standard deal of a dollar each way.
And if you got on his list early enough, well you could go and you could leave.
This is a fellow student?
And when, all right, and so you'd go on Saturday midday?
Well, yeah, because we had Saturday classes.
And that would be, just depending, maybe we'd leave Saturday morning or maybe we'd leave at noon Saturday.
Anyway, we'd take off up the road and we had a place to meet in Dallas to
get back together on Sunday afternoon and he'd get his back.
That was his name on the roof.
Now my roommate and his brother had a, as a sophomore, they had a 1941 maroon Mercury Converter for the white top.
That was about as hot as you could get.
And if his brother wasn't using it, well, I really could.
We made a few trips like that.
I made some others.
Let's say on a weekend in the Bryan College Station area, where did an Aggie undergraduate go for a good time on Friday night and or Saturday night?
Well, if the guy was turning the deer or run on what's a favorite in those days, he might go down to Fort Melbourne to Arlington and see what they had.
Tell me where that was and tell me about that, please.
It's about nine and a half, two miles south of the present point of the campus.
I've gone back and found it these days.
And I've been challenged to do so.
And it was H-Y-R-D-L-I-C-K-A, something like that?
H-R-D. H-R-D. L-I-K-A.
Right.
So a good Czech name, but pronounced by the average Aggie as hard liquors.
Yeah.
All right.
Was liquor legal then?
No.
Liquor was the closest liquor was cost over the call rate.
What did you all buy at hard liquors?
beer and some rum.
Oh so neither were were either of those legal or was that illegal in Brazos County?
Well after a while you got where you get it.
I tell you the truth I don't know.
I didn't drink in those days and didn't think me to go with them for it.
As far as you know what were the popular brands of beer that beer drinkers drank then?
All right.
Was it called... Was it called Whiskey Bridge then?
Okay.
Say later going straight west towards Snook and when you got into Burleson County there was a stop over there where legally you could buy whiskey.
Okay.
Describe the Northgate area.
What was over there, Northgate?
Well, as you went north from the A&M Post Office,
